\begin_layout Title
Lecture 7: Search in Continuous-Time 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Why Search and Matching?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Many assets can be illiquid, not only do to financial frictions, but also
 because because the environment doesn't allow to materialize gains from
 trade.
 A natural reason is that there is a buyer out there, willing to trade with
 a seller, but they cannot find each other.
 A natural market where this friction is relevant is the housing market.
 Search theory is naturally employed in many bilateral relations such as
 labor markets and the marriage market.
 However, a market as active as the FED funds market, operates in an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

over-the-counter
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 fashion, where agents don't know how much other agents want to trade.
 There is no centralized system that clears prices and quantities simultaneously
, as for example, with the stock market.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will cover a couple of topics in this lecture.
 First, I begin with a review of Poisson processes, as a starting point
 to think of Continuous Time events.
 Then I derive some basic Bellman equations.
 Then we will study two applications: The first is a variation of the seminal
 paper by Duffie Garleanu and Pedersen (2005, ECMA).
 This is a seminal paper that studies search in (Non-Walrasian) in over-the-coun
ter markets.
 The theoretical contribution is to present an explicit computation of allocatio
ns and prices in a setup with dynamic search and bargaining.
 The model is used to account for a liquidity premium and volumes of trade.
 The paper is a benchmark in several recent agendas, including work by Rob
 Shimer, Pierre Olivier Weill and Semih Uslu.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the second part of the notes, I connect this model with the model of
 money search of Lagos and Wright.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Preliminary: Poisson Processes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
From Bernoulli to Poisson.

\series default
 Divide the real line into a sequence of time 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\left\{ 1,2,3,...,\infty\right\} .$
\end_inset

 Assume that every periods, there is a chance of an occurrence of a given
 event.
 We let the random variable 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{y}=1$
\end_inset

 when the event has occurred by time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 This function is a random variable because it is a function defined in
 an underlying probability space.
 We let that probability be, 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Because the process is Bernoulli, it is independent by definition.
 Thus, the probability that an event has not occurred by period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is given by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Pr\left\{ N_{t}=0\right\} =\left(1-p\right)^{t}
\]

\end_inset

The chance that the event occurs exactly at time t+1 is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Pr\left\{ N_{t+1}=1|N_{t}=0\right\} =\left(1-p\right)^{t}p.
\]

\end_inset

Observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pr\left\{ N_{t+s}=0|N_{t}=0\right\} =\left(1-p\right)^{t}\left(1-p\right)^{t+s-t}=\left(1-p\right)^{t+s}=\Pr\left\{ N_{t+s}=0|N_{t}=0\right\} .$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\Pr\left\{ N_{t+s}=0|N_{t}=0\right\} }{\Pr\left\{ N_{t}=0\right\} }=\left(1-p\right)^{s}=\Pr\left\{ N_{s}=0\right\} .
\]

\end_inset

This process is is stationary.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, we want to study what happens as we divided the real line into a finer
 and finer sets of points.
 Thus, as we set 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\left\{ \Delta,2\Delta,...\infty\right\} .$
\end_inset

 However, we study the probability in this problem in a particular way.
 We cannot simply divide the real line into finer and finer points without
 adjusting the probability.
 Otherwise, as we continue doing so, we would eventually have infinite Bernoulli
 trials in a single period.
 Instead, we have to be more careful and specify a ratio for the probabilities:
 we fix a constant 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda\Delta=p\left(\Delta\right)
\]

\end_inset

Thus, as 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\rightarrow0,$
\end_inset

 the probability shrinks, but the rate at which it does is constant.
 The date can be divided into the number of intervals via:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
t=\Delta n\left(\Delta,t\right).
\]

\end_inset

Let's now compute the chances of seeing the event at a particular date:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Pr\left\{ N_{t}=1|N_{t-\Delta}=0\right\} =\left(1-p\left(\Delta\right)\right)^{n\left(\Delta,t\right)-\Delta}p\left(\Delta\right).
\]

\end_inset

Thus, we write this expression as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(1-\lambda\Delta\right)^{n\left(\Delta,t\right)-\Delta}\lambda\Delta.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since as 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\rightarrow0,$
\end_inset

 the probability of the event becomes a density, we can define the following
 density:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f\left(t;\lambda\right)=\lim_{\Delta\rightarrow\infty}\frac{\left(1-\lambda\Delta\right)^{n\left(\Delta,t\right)-\Delta}\lambda}{\Delta}\Delta.
\]

\end_inset

I'm skipping many steps from measure theory that prove the continuity of
 probabilities.
 For now, we can compute this object:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
 &  & \lim_{\Delta\rightarrow\infty}\left(1-\lambda\Delta\right)^{t/\Delta}\left(1-\lambda\Delta\right)^{-\Delta}\lambda\\
 & = & \left(\lim_{\Delta\rightarrow\infty}\left(1-\lambda\Delta\right)^{1/\Delta}\right)^{t}\lim_{\Delta\rightarrow\infty}\left(1-\lambda\Delta\right)^{-\Delta}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

and by definition of e, we obtain:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
 & = & \left(\lim_{\Delta\rightarrow\infty}\left(1-\lambda\Delta\right)^{1/\Delta}\right)^{t}\lim_{\Delta\rightarrow\infty}\left(1-\lambda\Delta\right)^{-\Delta}\lambda\\
 & = & \lambda\exp\left(-\lambda t\right).
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Let's integrate this density from zero to infinity:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{0}^{\infty}\lambda\exp\left(-\lambda t\right)dt=-\exp\left(-\lambda t\right)|_{0}^{\infty}=-0-\left(-1\right)=1.
\]

\end_inset

This is the density of the probability that the event occurs at time t.
 Naturally, the density of the event not occurring by 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 can be obtained in a similar way.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph

\series bold
Connection with Poisson Distribution.

\series default
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Poisson processes are understood as random 
\begin_inset Formula $N\left(\omega\right)$
\end_inset

 variable taking values in 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{+}$
\end_inset

.
 These are the only processes satisfying the conditions of independent increment
s, stationarity and that expected number of arrivals in a given fraction
 of time is constant.
 The distribution of a poisson counting process is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P\left(N=k\right)=\frac{\lambda^{k}e^{-\lambda}}{k!}
\]

\end_inset

A poisson processes is defined over the real line and there distribution,
 namely the distribution of an at a point t of time is.
 That is, it is exactly like the poisson counting process, except that we
 affect the probability of the counting process by where we are on the real
 line.
 Thus:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P\left(N_{t}=k\right)=\frac{\left(\lambda t\right)^{k}e^{-\lambda t}}{k!}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Additional useful property of the poisson process is its additivity characterist
ic; namely that X+Y poisson with rates 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{y},$
\end_inset

 it holds that :
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
N_{t}^{1}+N_{t}^{2}\sim\text{Poisson}(\lambda_{x}+\lambda_{y})
\]

\end_inset

The stopping time 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=\inf\left\{ s:N_{t+s}-N_{t}=1\right\} $
\end_inset

 has and exponential density with parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

, —the same as the parameter of the Poisson process that generated the stopping
 time:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tau\sim\lambda\cdot\exp(-\lambda t)
\]

\end_inset

so obviously the stopping time 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=\min(\tau_{1},\tau_{2})$
\end_inset

 for two independent poisson processes with rates 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{2}$
\end_inset

 is associated with the 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1}+X_{2}$
\end_inset

 poisson random variable.
 Therefore, its distribution is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tau\sim\left(\lambda_{1}+\lambda_{2}\right)\cdot\exp(-\left(\lambda_{1}+\lambda_{2}\right)t)
\]

\end_inset

Finally, 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left[\tau=\tau_{1}\right]$
\end_inset

 is computed as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P(\tau_{1}=t,N_{t}^{2}=0)=P(\tau_{1}=t)\cdot P(N_{t}^{2}=0)=\left(\lambda_{1}\cdot\exp(-\lambda_{1}t)\right)\cdot\exp\left(-\lambda_{2}t\right).
\]

\end_inset

which is the probability that 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{t}^{1}$
\end_inset

 jumps at t while 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{t}^{2}$
\end_inset

 remains at 0.
 Integrating over the whole domain yields:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\int_{o}^{\infty}\left(\lambda_{1}\cdot\exp(-\lambda_{1}t)\right)\cdot\exp\left(-\lambda_{2}t\right)dt & = & \int_{o}^{\infty}\exp\left(-\lambda_{2}t\right)dt-\int_{o}^{\infty}\exp\left(-\left(\lambda_{1}+\lambda_{2}\right)t\right)\lambda_{1}dt\\
 & = & \frac{\lambda_{1}}{\left(\lambda_{1}+\lambda_{2}\right)}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

and to check that this is correct we look at 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left[\tau=\tau_{1}\right]+P\left[\tau=\tau_{2}\right]$
\end_inset

, by symmetry:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\lambda_{1}}{\left(\lambda_{1}+\lambda_{2}\right)}+\frac{\lambda_{2}}{\left(\lambda_{1}+\lambda_{2}\right)}=1.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Critically, the time between two Poisson events is distributed exponential:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Pr\left[N_{t+\Delta}\ge N_{t}+1|N_{t}\right]=1-\exp\left(-\lambda\Delta\right).
\]

\end_inset

We make use of this distribution repeatedly below.
 The density is, of course, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f\left(N_{t+\Delta}\ge N_{t}+1|N_{t}\right)=1-\exp\left(-\lambda\Delta\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Hamilton-Jacobi-Bellman Equation 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Net present values in continuous time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now move on to study the continuous time version of Bellman equations.
 Let's begin first computing a net present value formula, without the maximizati
on.
 We try to compute:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V_{t}=\sum_{s=0}^{\infty}\beta^{t+s}U\left(c_{t+s}\right)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{t+s}$
\end_inset

 is a known path.
 We can conduct the following convenient change of variables and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=\exp\left(-\rho\right).$
\end_inset

 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 is approximately 
\begin_inset Formula $1-\beta.$
\end_inset

 Thus, we can write the expression as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V_{t}=\sum_{s=0}^{\infty}\exp\left(-\rho\left(s\right)\right)U\left(c_{t+s}\right).
\]

\end_inset

We want to make the same computations as time intervals, become smaller
 and smaller, as we did with the Bernoulli example above.
 Naturally, we need to weight utility by the length of the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

, to make things consistent.
 Thus, the value is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V\left(t,\Delta\right)=\sum_{s=0:\Delta:\infty}\exp\left(-\rho\left(t+s\right)\right)U\left(c_{t+s}\right)\Delta.
\]

\end_inset

Taking the limit yields, by definition of Lebesgue integral, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lim_{\Delta\rightarrow0}V\left(t,\Delta\right)=\int_{0}^{\infty}\exp\left(-\rho s\right)U\left(c_{t+s}\right)ds.
\]

\end_inset

From now on, abandon the notation that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

 for the time interval and we use it to compute derivatives.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, we want to compute how the value changes as a function of calendar
 time.
 Thus, we compute:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{V\left(t+\Delta\right)-V\left(t\right)}{\Delta}.
\]

\end_inset

Why are we interested in this object? Because it will be useful to characterize
 Continuous Time problems that often do not have solutions in discrete time.
 By definition we have:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
V\left(t+\Delta\right)-V\left(t\right) & = & \int_{0}^{\infty}\exp\left(-\rho s\right)U\left(c_{t+\Delta+s}\right)ds-\int_{0}^{\infty}\exp\left(-\rho s\right)U\left(c_{t+s}\right)ds\\
 & = & \int_{0}^{\infty}\exp\left(-\rho s\right)U\left(c_{t+\Delta+s}\right)ds-\int_{0}^{\Delta}\exp\left(-\rho s\right)U\left(c_{t+s}\right)ds-\int_{\Delta}^{\infty}\exp\left(-\rho s\right)U\left(c_{t+s}\right)ds\\
 & = & \int_{0}^{\infty}\exp\left(-\rho s\right)U\left(c_{t+\Delta+s}\right)ds-\int_{0}^{\Delta}\exp\left(-\rho s\right)U\left(c_{t+s}\right)ds-\int_{0}^{\infty}\exp\left(-\rho\left(z+\Delta\right)\right)U\left(c_{t+z}\right)dz
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where the last line is a change of variables 
\begin_inset Formula $z=s+\Delta.$
\end_inset

 Thus, we have:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V\left(t+\Delta\right)-V\left(t\right)=\left(1-\exp\left(-\rho\Delta\right)\right)\int_{0}^{\infty}\exp\left(-\rho s\right)U\left(c_{t+\Delta+s}\right)ds-\int_{0}^{\Delta}\exp\left(-\rho s\right)U\left(c_{t+s}\right)ds.
\]

\end_inset

Then, we obtain:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lim_{\Delta\rightarrow0}\frac{V\left(t+\Delta\right)-V\left(t\right)}{\Delta}=\lim_{\Delta\rightarrow0}\frac{\left(1-\exp\left(-\rho\Delta\right)\right)}{\Delta}\int_{0}^{\infty}\exp\left(-\rho s\right)U\left(c_{t+\Delta+s}\right)ds-\lim_{\Delta\rightarrow0}\frac{\int_{0}^{\Delta}\exp\left(-\rho s\right)U\left(c_{t+s}\right)ds}{\Delta}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The next line just follows a number of definitions.
 Thus, we have:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{V}=\lim_{\Delta\rightarrow0}\frac{\left(1-\exp\left(-\rho\Delta\right)\right)}{\Delta}\cdot\lim_{\Delta\rightarrow0}\int_{0}^{\infty}\exp\left(-\rho s\right)U\left(c_{t+\Delta+s}\right)ds-\lim_{\Delta\rightarrow0}\frac{\int_{0}^{\Delta}\exp\left(-\rho s\right)U\left(c_{t+s}\right)ds-\int_{0}^{0}\exp\left(-\rho s\right)U\left(c_{t+s}\right)ds}{\Delta}.
\]

\end_inset

The last term can be evaluated via Leibnitz's rule.
 First term, is the product of two limits.
 Note that: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lim_{\Delta\rightarrow0}\frac{\exp\left(-\rho\Delta\right)-1}{\Delta}\equiv\frac{\partial\exp\left(-\rho\Delta\right)}{\partial\Delta}|_{\Delta=0}=-\rho.
\]

\end_inset

and
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\lim_{\Delta\rightarrow0}\frac{\int_{0}^{\Delta}\exp\left(-\rho s\right)U\left(c_{t+s}\right)ds-\int_{0}^{0}\exp\left(-\rho s\right)U\left(c_{t+s}\right)ds}{\Delta} & \equiv & \frac{\partial\int_{0}^{\Delta}\exp\left(-\rho s\right)U\left(c_{t+s}\right)ds}{\partial\Delta}|_{\Delta=0}\\
 & = & \exp\left(-\rho\Delta\right)U\left(c_{t+\Delta}\right)|_{s=0}=U\left(c_{t}\right).
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus, we have:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\dot{V} & = & \rho\cdot\lim_{\Delta\rightarrow0}\int_{0}^{\infty}\exp\left(-\rho s\right)U\left(c_{t+\Delta+s}\right)ds-U\left(c_{t}\right)\rightarrow\\
\rho V & = & \dot{V}+U\left(c_{t+s}\right).
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

I assumed to this point that 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is a constant, then 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{t}$
\end_inset

 is a constant, and we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{V}=0$
\end_inset

.
 In this case, we obtain: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V=U\left(c\right)/\rho.
\]

\end_inset

This is nothing but the famous net present value function.
 It's is the continuous-time analogue of 
\begin_inset Formula $U\left(c\right)/\left(1-\beta\right)$
\end_inset

.
 This approximation is exact for 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

—although the net-present value is undefined.
\end_layout

