\series default
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $c\left(S\right)=\bar{c}\cdot S$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\left(s\right)=\left(r-\bar{c}\right)\cdot S$
\end_inset

.
 How do you interpret this terms? Assume 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is a power utility: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U\left(C\right)=\frac{C^{1-\sigma}-1}{1-\sigma}.
\]

\end_inset

Show that the value function is of the form:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V(S)=\frac{AS^{1-\sigma}-B}{1-\sigma},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 are undetermined coefficients.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
The proof is by Guess and Verify where I match coefficients:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V(S)=\frac{AS^{1-\sigma}-B}{1-\sigma}.
\]

\end_inset

Note that under the conjecture:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho V=\frac{\bar{c}^{1-\sigma}S^{1-\sigma}}{1-\sigma}+AS^{1-\sigma}\left(r-\bar{c}\right)-\frac{1}{1-\sigma}.
\]

\end_inset

Grouping terms:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho V=\frac{\left(\bar{c}^{1-\sigma}+\left(1-\sigma\right)\left(r-\bar{c}\right)A\right)}{1-\sigma}S^{1-\sigma}-\frac{1}{1-\sigma}
\]

\end_inset

What if c
\begin_inset Formula $_{t}$
\end_inset

 varies with time? Can you find the solution to 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

? Thus, matching coefficients, we obtain:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho A=\bar{c}^{1-\sigma}+\left(1-\sigma\right)\left(r-\bar{c}\right)A\rightarrow A=\frac{\bar{c}^{1-\sigma}}{\rho-\left(1-\sigma\right)\left(r-\bar{c}\right)}.
\]

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $B=1/\rho$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
When Consumption is Maximized.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What if consumption is actually maximized.
 Since the HJB equation is valid for any path of 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{t}$
\end_inset

, optimal consumption will maximize:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V=\max_{c}U\left(c\right)+V_{s}\mu\left(S,c\right)S+\dot{V}
\]

\end_inset

if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\left(S,c\right)$
\end_inset

 is a control variable.
 This is true because the problem does not depend on past decisions—the
 principle of optimality.
 Hence, the reference to Richard Bellman.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph

\series bold
Example II.

\series default
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\left(s\right)=r\cdot S-c$
\end_inset

 but let 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 be now maximized.
 Assume 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is a power utility: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U\left(C\right)=\frac{C^{1-\sigma}-1}{1-\sigma}.
\]

\end_inset

Show that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V(S)=\frac{AS^{1-\sigma}-B}{1-\sigma},
\]

\end_inset

where
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $A=\left(\frac{\rho-\left(1-\sigma\right)r}{\sigma}\right)^{-\sigma}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B=1/\rho$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
The proof is by Guess and Verify where I match coefficients:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V(S)=\frac{AS^{1-\sigma}-B}{1-\sigma}.
\]

\end_inset

Note that under the conjecture:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U'\left(c\right)=V_{s}=AS^{-\sigma}\rightarrow c=\left(AS^{-\sigma}\right)^{-1/\sigma}=A^{-1/\sigma}S.
\]

\end_inset

This implies that the solution to the previous example is identical, but
 now must solve a fixed point.
 Namely, it must be that 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{c}=A^{-1/\sigma}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Thus, this implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{c}=A/\left(1-\sigma\right)$
\end_inset

 in the previous example.
 Thus:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho\frac{A}{1-\sigma}=\frac{A^{1-1/\sigma}}{1-\sigma}+rA-A^{1-1/\sigma}
\]

\end_inset

Simplifying terms by dividing both sides by 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, we obtain:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\rho}{1-\sigma}=\frac{\sigma}{1-\sigma}A^{-1/\sigma}+r,
\]

\end_inset

and from here:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A^{-1/\sigma}=\frac{\rho-\left(1-\sigma\right)r}{\sigma}.
\]

\end_inset

The proof for 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is the same as above.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can connect this term with the Euler Equation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{c}=A^{-1/\sigma}\dot{S}=A^{-1/\sigma}\left(r-\bar{c}\right)S=A^{-1/\sigma}\frac{\sigma r-\rho+\left(1-\sigma\right)r}{\sigma}S=A^{-1/\sigma}\frac{r-\rho}{\sigma}S
\]

\end_inset

The Euler equation will be derived from first principles later, but here
 note that:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\dot{c}}{c}=\frac{r-\rho}{\sigma}S.
\]

\end_inset

We will encounter this Euler equation in multiple places.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
HJB equation with Poisson Events
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Two Consecutive Events Cannot Happen.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A first observation regards the possibility of two subsequent events.
 Recall that the probability that the first Poisson event is exponential.
 By independence, we can show:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Pr\left[N_{t+\Delta}\geq1|N_{t}=0\right]=1-\exp\left(-\lambda\Delta\right)
\]

\end_inset

and likewise, the probability that two events happen is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Pr\left[N_{t+\Delta}\geq2|N_{t}=0\right]=\int_{0}^{\Delta}\lambda\exp\left(-\lambda\tau\right)\cdot\left(1-\exp\left(-\lambda\left(\Delta-\tau\right)\right)\right)d\tau.
\]

\end_inset

Then, consider:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lim_{\Delta\downarrow0}\frac{\Pr\left[N_{t+\Delta}\geq1\right]}{\Delta}=\lim_{\Delta\downarrow0}\frac{1-\exp\left(-\lambda\Delta\right)}{\Delta}=\lambda.
\]

\end_inset

But now for 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pr\left[N_{t+\Delta}\geq2|N_{t}=0\right]$
\end_inset

, notice that:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lim_{\Delta\downarrow0}\frac{\Pr\left[N_{t+\Delta}\geq2|N_{t}=0\right]}{\Delta}=\lim_{\Delta\downarrow0}\int_{0}^{\Delta}\left(1-\exp\left(-\lambda\tau\right)\right)\cdot\frac{\left(1-\exp\left(-\lambda\left(\Delta-\tau\right)\right)\right)}{\Delta}d\tau=0.
\]

\end_inset

This can be verified since the term inside cannot blow up.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Consecutive Jumps.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now move on to Hamilton-Jacobi-Bellman equation, but allowing Jumps.
 We compute:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V\left(t,X_{t}\right)=\mathbb{E}\left[\int_{0}^{\infty}\exp\left(-\rho s\right)U\left(c_{t+s}\right)ds|X_{t}\right].
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{t+s}$
\end_inset

 is a Poisson process.
 What do we mean by this? It's a process that switches value upon the realizatio
n of a Poisson event.
 We can think of 
\begin_inset Formula $|X_{t}$
\end_inset

 as the conditioning over a state given by the value before the switch.
 For example, 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{t}\in\left\{ L,H\right\} $
\end_inset

 implies that there are only two states.
 For simplicity, here I assume it takes high and low values, thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $c=C\left(X\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We start with 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{t}=H,$
\end_inset

 for simplicity.
 The expectation refers to the current state.
 We compute the value as before, regarding a short time interval.
 We split the integral between two terms:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
V\left(t,H\right) & = & \mathbb{E}\left[\int_{0}^{\Delta}\exp\left(-\rho s\right)U\left(c\left(X_{t}\right)\right)ds|X_{0}=H\right]\\
 & + & \exp\left(-\rho\Delta\right)\mathbb{E}\left[\mathbb{E}\left[\int_{\Delta}^{\infty}\exp\left(-\rho s\right)U\left(c\left(X_{t}\right)\right)ds|X_{t+\Delta}=H\right]|,X_{0}=H\right]\\
 & + & \exp\left(-\rho\Delta\right)\mathbb{E}\left[\mathbb{E}\left[\int_{\Delta}^{\infty}\exp\left(-\rho s\right)U\left(c\left(X_{t}\right)\right)ds|X_{t+\Delta}=L\right]|,X_{0}=H\right].
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Consider the probability of only one switch, ignoring the probabilities
 of more than one switch by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
V\left(t,H\right) & = & \mathbb{E}\left[\int_{0}^{\Delta}\exp\left(-\rho s\right)U\left(c\left(X_{t+s}\right)\right)ds|X_{0}=H\right]\\
 & + & \exp\left(-\rho\Delta\right)\exp\left(-\lambda\Delta\right)\mathbb{E}\left[\int_{\Delta}^{\infty}\exp\left(-\rho s\right)U\left(c\left(X_{t+s}\right)\right)ds|X_{t+\Delta}=H\right]\\
 & + & \exp\left(-\rho\Delta\right)\left(1-\exp\left(-\lambda\Delta\right)\right)\mathbb{E}\left[\int_{\Delta}^{\infty}\exp\left(-\rho s\right)U\left(c\left(X_{t}\right)\right)ds|X_{t+\Delta}=L\right]+O\left(\Delta\right).
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Then, exploiting the Markovian structure:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
V\left(t,H\right) & = & \mathbb{E}\left[\int_{0}^{\Delta}\exp\left(-\rho s\right)U\left(c\left(X_{t+s}\right)\right)ds|X_{0}=H\right]\\
 & + & \exp\left(-\left(\rho+\lambda\right)\Delta\right)V\left(t+\Delta,H\right)\\
 & + & \exp\left(-\rho\Delta\right)\left(1-\exp\left(-\lambda\Delta\right)\right)V\left(t+\Delta,L\right)+O\left(\Delta\right).
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We perform the same operation as before, subtracting 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(t+\Delta,H\right)$
\end_inset

 from both sides.
 We obtain:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
V\left(t,H\right)-V\left(t+\Delta,H\right) & = & \mathbb{E}\left[\int_{0}^{\Delta}\exp\left(-\rho s\right)U\left(c\left(X_{t+s}\right)\right)ds|X_{0}=H\right]\\
 & + & \left(\exp\left(-\left(\rho+\lambda\right)\Delta\right)-1\right)V\left(t+\Delta,H\right)+\exp\left(-\rho\Delta\right)\left(1-\exp\left(-\lambda\Delta\right)\right)V\left(t+\Delta,L\right)+O\left(\Delta\right).
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Dividing by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

 and taking limits, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\lim_{\Delta\downarrow0}\frac{V\left(t,H\right)-V\left(t+\Delta,H\right)}{\Delta} & = & \lim_{\Delta\downarrow0}\frac{\mathbb{E}\left[\int_{0}^{\Delta}\exp\left(-\rho s\right)U\left(c\left(X_{t}\right)\right)ds|X_{0}=H\right]}{\Delta}\\
 & + & \lim_{\Delta\downarrow0}\frac{\left(\exp\left(-\left(\rho+\lambda\right)\Delta\right)-1\right)}{\Delta}\lim_{\Delta\downarrow0}V\left(t+\Delta,H\right)\\
 & + & \lim_{\Delta\downarrow0}\exp\left(-\rho\Delta\right)\lim_{\Delta\downarrow0}\frac{\left(1-\exp\left(-\lambda\Delta\right)\right)}{\Delta}\lim_{\Delta\downarrow0}V\left(t+\Delta,L\right)+\lim_{\Delta\downarrow0}\frac{O\left(\Delta\right)}{\Delta}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

From the same arguments used above, we arrive at:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho V\left(t,H\right)=U\left(c\left(H\right)\right)+\lambda\left[V\left(t,L\right)-V\left(t,H\right)\right]+\dot{V},
\]

\end_inset

and by analogy:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho V\left(t,L\right)=U\left(c\left(L\right)\right)+\lambda\left[V\left(t,H\right)-V\left(t,L\right)\right]+\dot{V}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

