\begin_layout Standard
When the agent switches type, they agent can go to a market and trade the
 asset immediately.
 Let's assume that when this happens, agents can sell assets, but if there
 is excess demand in one market, the price of the asset corresponds to the
 value of the side that has excess demand (for selling or buying the asset).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By assumption, sellers must be indifferent between buying or not.
 For starters, assume that every time agents switch, they can immediately
 sell or buy the asset.
 The value function for a high type that owns the asset is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho V\left(h,o\right)=U\left(1\right)+\lambda\left[V\left(\ell,o\right)-V\left(h,o\right)\right],
\]

\end_inset

if the agent does not own the asset: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho V\left(h,n\right)=U\left(0\right)+\lambda\left[V\left(\ell,n\right)-V\left(h,n\right)\right].
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The value function captures the idea that when the agent becomes a low type,
 and owns the asset, it will sell it.
 Likewise, if it doesn't own the asset, it won't buy it when it becomes
 a low type.
 It must be the case that, because the market is Walrasian, and the asset
 can be sold immediately, this agent must be indifferent between buying
 and selling.
 Hence, we obtain:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V\left(h,n\right)=V\left(h,o\right)-P.
\]

\end_inset

The condition for an equilibrium is that the agent be indifferent between
 buying or not buying the asset.
 This is because the asset is rationed.
 Hence, the value for the low type must be:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho V\left(\ell,n\right)=\delta U\left(0\right)+\lambda\left[\max\left\{ V\left(h,n\right),V\left(h,o\right)-P\right\} -V\left(\ell,n\right)\right],
\]

\end_inset

but using the indifference condition above, this equation simplifies to:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho V\left(\ell,n\right)=\delta U\left(0\right)+\lambda\left[V\left(h,n\right)-V\left(\ell,n\right)\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since, by assumption, all low types sell the asset, and the agent will sell
 it immediately, if he switches type, the low types must be related as follows:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V\left(\ell,n\right)+P\leq V\left(\ell,o\right).
\]

\end_inset

However, if indeed the asset is sold immediately—as we are in continuous
 time.
 Thus, it must be the case that 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\ell,n\right)+P=V\left(\ell,o\right).$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can subtract the first two valuation equations to obtain a single condition.
 The condition is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\rho\left(V\left(h,o\right)-V\left(h,n\right)\right) & = & U\left(1\right)-U\left(0\right)+\lambda\left(V\left(\ell,o\right)-V\left(h,o\right)-(V\left(\ell,n\right)-V\left(h,n\right))\right).
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Using the relationship with 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

, we obtain:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P=\frac{U\left(1\right)-U\left(0\right)}{\rho}.
\]

\end_inset

Thus, the ownership yields the same value regardless of the type switching
 of types.
 The ability to buy an sell a scarce asset, yields the valuation of the
 highest marginal type in society: The value is discounted for time, 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

, for the value of holding it—the asset cannot be burned or consumed.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hence, we obtain that the equilibrium in terms of value satisfies:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho V\left(h,o\right)=U\left(1\right)+\lambda\left[V\left(\ell,n\right)+\lambda P-V\left(h,o\right)\right],
\]

\end_inset

if the agent does not own the asset: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho V\left(h,n\right)=U\left(0\right)+\lambda\left[V\left(\ell,n\right)-V\left(h,n\right)\right],
\]

\end_inset

while for the low state:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho V\left(\ell,n\right)=\delta U\left(0\right)+\lambda\left[V\left(h,n\right)-V\left(\ell,n\right)\right].
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Subtracting the last two equations:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V\left(h,n\right)-V\left(\ell,n\right)=\frac{\left(1-\delta\right)}{\rho}U\left(0\right).
\]

\end_inset

Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho V\left(h,o\right)=U\left(1\right)+\lambda\left[V\left(\ell,n\right)-V\left(h,n\right)-P\right]+\lambda P,
\]

\end_inset

then yields:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V\left(h,o\right)=\frac{U\left(1\right)+\lambda\left[V\left(\ell,n\right)-V\left(h,n\right)\right]}{\rho}=\frac{U\left(1\right)}{\rho}+\frac{\lambda}{\rho}\frac{\left(1-\delta\right)}{\rho}U\left(0\right).
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V\left(h,n\right)=V\left(h,o\right)-P=\frac{U\left(0\right)}{\rho}\left[1+\lambda\frac{\left(1-\delta\right)}{\rho}\right].
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Trading Frictions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now consider the case where the asset cannot be sold immediately.
 Rather, they can access the market with intensity 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

.
 We obtain:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\rho V\left(h,o\right) & = & U\left(1\right)+\lambda\left[V\left(\ell,o\right)-V\left(h,o\right)\right]\\
 &  & +\mu\underbrace{\left[\max\left\{ V\left(h,o\right),V\left(h,n\right)+P\right\} -V\left(h,o\right)\right]}_{\text{trading chance}}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

if the agent does not own the asset: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho V\left(h,n\right)=U\left(0\right)+\lambda\left[V\left(\ell,n\right)-V\left(h,n\right)\right]+\mu\left[\max\left\{ V\left(h,o\right)-P,V\left(h,n\right)\right\} -V\left(h,n\right)\right]
\]

\end_inset

For the low type owning the asset, we obtain:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho V\left(\ell,o\right)=\delta U\left(1\right)+\lambda\left[V\left(\ell,o\right)-V\left(h,o\right)\right]+\mu\left[V\left(\ell,n\right)+P-V\left(\ell,o\right)\right].
\]

\end_inset

Finally, we have the value of the low type that doesn't own the asset:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho V\left(\ell,n\right)=\delta U\left(0\right)+\lambda\left[V\left(\ell,n\right)-V\left(h,n\right)\right]+\mu\left[\max\left\{ V\left(n,o\right)-P,V\left(\ell,n\right)\right\} -V\left(\ell,n\right)\right].
\]

\end_inset

Since again, the seller high type accessing the market must be indifferent
 between having the asset or not (since the asset is scarce)
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P=V\left(h,o\right)-V\left(h,n\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus, the value functions can be written as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho V\left(h,o\right)=U\left(1\right)+\lambda\left[V\left(\ell,o\right)-V\left(h,o\right)\right]
\]

\end_inset

if the agent does not own the asset: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho V\left(h,n\right)=U\left(0\right)+\lambda\left[V\left(\ell,n\right)-V\left(h,n\right)\right].
\]

\end_inset

For the low type owning the asset, we obtain:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho V\left(\ell,o\right)=\delta U\left(1\right)+\lambda\left[V\left(\ell,o\right)-V\left(h,o\right)\right]+\mu\left[V\left(h,o\right)-V\left(h,n\right)-\left(V\left(\ell,o\right)-V\left(\ell,n\right)\right)\right].
\]

\end_inset

Finally, we have the value of the low type that doesn't own the asset:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho V\left(\ell,n\right)=\delta U\left(0\right)+\lambda\left[V\left(\ell,n\right)-V\left(h,n\right)\right]+\mu\left[\max\left\{ V\left(n,o\right)-P,V\left(\ell,n\right)\right\} -V\left(\ell,n\right)\right].
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Conjecture again that 
\begin_inset Formula $\max\left\{ V\left(n,o\right)-P,V\left(\ell,n\right)\right\} =V\left(\ell,n\right).$
\end_inset

 Thus, we obtain:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho V\left(\ell,n\right)=\delta U\left(0\right)+\lambda\left[V\left(\ell,n\right)-V\left(h,n\right)\right].
\]

\end_inset

We can solve this terms, as they are 4 equations with 4 unknowns:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\rho+\lambda\right)V\left(h,o\right)=U\left(1\right)+\lambda V\left(\ell,o\right)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\rho+\lambda\right)V\left(h,n\right)=U\left(0\right)+\lambda V\left(\ell,n\right)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho V\left(\ell,o\right)=\delta U\left(1\right)+\lambda\left[V\left(h,o\right)-V\left(\ell,o\right)\right]+\mu\left[V\left(h,o\right)-V\left(h,n\right)-\left(V\left(\ell,o\right)-V\left(\ell,n\right)\right)\right]
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho V\left(\ell,n\right)=\delta U\left(0\right)+\lambda\left[V\left(h,n\right)-V\left(\ell,n\right)\right].
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We need to solve for the values now.
 There are four unknowns and for equations.
 Subtract the fourth from the third equation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho\left[V\left(\ell,o\right)-V\left(\ell,n\right)\right]=\delta\left[U\left(1\right)-U\left(0\right)\right]-\lambda\left[V\left(\ell,o\right)-V\left(\ell,n\right)-\left(V\left(h,o\right)-V\left(h,n\right)\right)\right]+\mu\left[V\left(h,o\right)-V\left(h,n\right)-\left(V\left(\ell,o\right)-V\left(\ell,n\right)\right)\right]
\]

\end_inset

Grouping terms we obtain:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[V\left(\ell,o\right)-V\left(\ell,n\right)\right]=\delta\frac{\left[U\left(1\right)-U\left(0\right)\right]}{\left(\rho+\lambda+\mu\right)}+\frac{\lambda+\mu}{\rho+\lambda+\mu}\left(V\left(h,o\right)-V\left(h,n\right)\right).
\]

\end_inset

Likewise from the first two equations:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V\left(h,o\right)-V\left(h,n\right)=\frac{U\left(1\right)-U\left(0\right)}{\left(\rho+\lambda\right)}+\frac{\lambda}{\left(\rho+\lambda\right)}\left[V\left(\ell,o\right)-V\left(\ell,n\right)\right].
\]

\end_inset

The system simplifies to a system of two equations and two unknowns.
 Substituting in:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V\left(h,o\right)-V\left(h,n\right)=\frac{\left[U\left(1\right)-U\left(0\right)\right]}{\left(\rho+\lambda\right)}\left[1+\frac{\lambda\delta}{\rho+\lambda+\mu}\right]+\frac{\lambda}{\left(\rho+\lambda\right)}\frac{\left(\lambda+\mu\right)}{\left(\rho+\lambda+\mu\right)}\left[V\left(h,o\right)-V\left(h,n\right)\right].
\]

\end_inset

Arranging term:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left[\frac{\left(\rho+\lambda+\mu\right)\left(\rho+\lambda\right)-\lambda\left(\lambda+\mu\right)}{\left(\rho+\lambda\right)\left(\rho+\lambda+\mu\right)}\right]\left[V\left(h,o\right)-V\left(h,n\right)\right] & = & \frac{\left[U\left(1\right)-U\left(0\right)\right]}{\left(\rho+\lambda\right)}\left[\frac{\rho\left(\rho+\lambda\right)+\rho\left(\lambda+\mu\right)+\lambda\left(\lambda+\mu\right)-\lambda\left(\lambda+\mu\right)}{\left(\rho+\lambda\right)\left(\rho+\lambda+\mu\right)}\right]\\
 & = & \frac{\left[U\left(1\right)-U\left(0\right)\right]}{\left(\rho+\lambda\right)}\left[\frac{\rho\left(\rho+\lambda\right)+\rho\left(\lambda+\mu\right)}{\left(\rho+\lambda\right)\left(\rho+\lambda+\mu\right)}\right].
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

The term:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\frac{\left(\rho+\lambda+\mu\right)-\lambda\left(\lambda+\mu\right)}{\left(\rho+\lambda\right)\left(\rho+\lambda+\mu\right)}\right]=\left[\frac{\rho\left(\rho+\lambda\right)+\rho\left(\lambda+\mu\right)}{\left(\rho+\lambda\right)\left(\rho+\lambda+\mu\right)}\right].
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally we arrive at:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P=\left[V\left(h,o\right)-V\left(h,n\right)\right]=\frac{\left[U\left(1\right)-U\left(0\right)\right]}{\rho}\left[\frac{\rho+\left(\delta+1\right)\lambda+\mu}{\rho+2\lambda+\mu}\right].
\]

\end_inset

