\begin_layout Standard
Consider now the problem of an agent that holds wealth in the form of bonds
 and cash.
 Importantly, cash is printed by the government every period—it is outside
 money—and thus, prone to inflationary taxes.
 Bonds are real and pay an interest.
 Money does not.
 We have that every period, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
W_{t}=b_{t}+m_{t}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The money and bond account can be traded in every period.
 For simplicity, let the portfolio weights be given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega^{b}$
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega^{m}$
\end_inset

, respectively.
 We will see that unlike other environments, the portfolio weights depend
 on wealth.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Wealth evolves according to:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{W}_{t}=r_{t}b_{t}-\pi_{t}m_{t}-c_{t}+h_{t}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the rate of inflation, 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{t}$
\end_inset

 an equilibrium rate in the bond market, 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{t}$
\end_inset

 consumption and 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{t}$
\end_inset

 hours worked.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Money is clearly a different asset than bonds here.
 The question is why does it pay different returns? The key assumption is
 that money can be used for transactions.
 Namely, with agents can meet other agents with Poisson probability and
 engage in a transaction over which they will bargain.
 For now, assume 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}\left(m\right)$
\end_inset

 is the value of holding money in a transaction.
 In turn, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 the value of selling: this just gives a value, some constant number.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The value function is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho V\left(W\right)=\max_{c,h}U\left(c\right)-h+V_{w}\dot{W}+\lambda\left[\mathcal{B}\left(m\right)+V\left(W-t\left(m\right)\right)-V\left(W\right)\right]+\lambda\left[\mathcal{G}+\int_{\tilde{m}}V\left(W-t\left(\tilde{m}\right)\right)-V\left(W\right)\right].
\]

\end_inset

The objects stand for the optimal transactions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A first key step, independent of the value of cash transactions is to establish
 the linearity of the value function.
 In particular, the first-order condition of this problem involve:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U'\left(c\right)=V_{w},\quad V_{w}=1.
\]

\end_inset

Thus, I guess and verify that the value function is affine:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V\left(W\right)=V_{o}+W.
\]

\end_inset

If this is indeed the case, we have that:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{W}_{t}=r_{t}\left(W_{t}-m_{t}\right)-\pi_{t}m_{t}-c_{t}+h_{t}.
\]

\end_inset

If the conjecture is to be verified: it must be the case that:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r_{t}=\rho.
\]

\end_inset

Then, the FOC for money balances is given by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho+\pi=\mathcal{B}'\left(m\right).
\]

\end_inset

This equation reflects a liquidity service of money relative to bonds.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A critical step in translating the model into continuous time is to introduce
 the wealth account: otherwise we have an issue.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Liquidity Service of Money.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next, I delve into the monetary holdings.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{B}\left(m\right)=\eta\mathcal{S}\left(m\right)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{G}\left(m\right)=\left(1-\eta\right)\mathcal{S}\left(m\right)
\]

\end_inset

Where total surplus is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{S}\left(m\right)=\max(u(\ell)-t)^{\eta}(-\ell+t)^{1-\eta}
\]

\end_inset

subject to:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
t\leq m.
\]

\end_inset

First order conditions:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\eta}{u(\ell)-t}\cdot\mathcal{S}\left(m\right)=\frac{1-\eta}{t-\ell}\cdot\mathcal{S}\left(m\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore, coupling terms together:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\eta\left(u(\ell)-\ell\right)=u(\ell)-t
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(1-\eta\right)\left(u(\ell)-\ell\right)=t-\ell.
\]

\end_inset

From here, note that:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{S}\left(m\right)=\eta^{\eta}\left(1-\eta\right)^{1-\eta}\times\left(u(\ell)-\ell\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The way to improve welfare is to first maximize total surplus and the split:
 in this case, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u'\left(\ell\right)=1
\]

\end_inset

is enough to maximize the surplus.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, surplus cannot be maximized if:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(1-\eta\right)u(\ell^{*})+\eta\ell^{*}\leq m,
\]

\end_inset

in which case, the constraint is binding.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus, in that case:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(1-\eta\right)u(\ell)+\eta\ell=m,
\]

\end_inset

and thus:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d\ell}{dm}=\frac{1}{\left(\left(1-\eta\right)u'(\ell)+\eta\right)}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

